<h1>Problem 502 - 2013 ELMO, P6 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Consider a function \(f: \mathbb Z \to \mathbb Z\) such that for every integer \(n \ge 0\), there are at most \(0.001n^2\) pairs of integers \((x,y)\) for which \(f(x+y) \neq f(x)+f(y)\) and \(\max\{ \lvert x \rvert, \lvert y \rvert \} \le n\). Is it possible that for some integer \(n \ge 0\), there are more than \(n\) integers \(a\) such that \(f(a) \neq a \cdot f(1)\) and \(\lvert a \rvert \le n\)?</p>
